<subSubSection id="838E00D39E69FFE6FF48FEF1F970FC5D" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="key">
<key id="BF0504699E69FFE6FF48FEF1F970FC5D" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyStep id="70604BFD9E69FFE6FF48FEF1F971FDBE" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="CB2B53589E69FFE6FF48FEF1F970FE2E" blockId="3.[189,1399,315,593]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="7065F06D9E69FFE6FF48FEF1F970FE2E" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
1. Frontal vitta at vertex level usually wider than at lunula level, often yellow to light-tawny anteriorly. Wing with hyaline portion inside cell dm and forming a characteristic sinuosity in the hyaline border. Dm-cu crossvein almost straight or slightly curved. Claws dark-tawny with darker tips ……………………………………………………………………… 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FBF7FE6CF970FE2E" authority="Townsend, 1915" authorityName="Townsend" authorityYear="1915" box="[1026,1399,422,449]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Ectophasiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FBF7FE6CF8B0FE2E" bold="true" box="[1026,1207,422,449]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ectophasiopsis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="AF052EA99E69FFE6FB4FFE6CF970FE2E" author="Townsend" box="[1210,1399,422,449]" firstAuthor="Townsend" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="405 - 440" refId="ref12962" refString="Townsend C. H. T. 1915. New Neotropical muscoid flies. Proceedings of the National Museum 49 (2115): 405 - 440. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.2115.405" type="journal article" year="1915">Townsend,1915</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB2B53589E69FFE6FF34FE01F971FDBE" blockId="3.[189,1399,315,593]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="7065F06D9E69FFE6FF34FE01F971FDBE" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">– Frontal vitta at lunula level usually wider than at vertex level (or subequal), tawny to dark-tawny, at most with some lighter spots. Hyaline portion of wing outside cell dm (if inside, only slightly, not forming sinuosity). Dm-cu crossvein usually curved, sometimes even sinuous. Claws yellow to pale-tawny with black tips ………………………………………………………………………2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70604BFD9E69FFE6FF48FDB3F970FC5D" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="CB2B53589E69FFE6FF48FDB3F970FD10" blockId="3.[189,1399,633,947]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="7065F06D9E69FFE6FF48FDB3F970FD10" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
2. Male: cerci weakly concave before posteromedian process, and posterolateral lobes absent or weakly developed. Postgonite distally very broad, in posterior view. Female: cerci thick, posteriorly flattened, with the flattened surfaces covered with rows of small setulae (for male and female terminalia, please see figures in 
<bibRefCitation id="AF052EA99E69FFE6FD91FD2EFF40FD10" author="Dios &amp; Nihei" box="[612,839,740,767]" firstAuthor="Dios" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="194 - 200" refId="ref12325" refString="Dios R. V. P. &amp; Nihei S. S. 2016. A remarkable new species of Eutrichopoda Townsend, 1908 (Diptera: Tachinidae: Phasiinae). Zootaxa 4121 (2): 194 - 200. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4121.2.10" type="journal article" year="2016">Dios &amp; Nihei 2016</bibRefCitation>
) ……………… 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FBF2FD2EF970FD10" authority="Townsend, 1908" authorityName="Townsend" authorityYear="1908" box="[1031,1399,740,767]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Eutrichopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FBF2FD2EF8AAFD10" bold="true" box="[1031,1197,740,767]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Eutrichopoda</emphasis>
Townsend, 1908
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB2B53589E69FFE6FF34FCC3F970FC5D" blockId="3.[189,1399,633,947]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead id="7065F06D9E69FFE6FF34FCC3F970FC5D" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
– Male: cerci usually concave before posteromedian process, and posterolateral lobes developed or moderately developed. Postgonite distally moderately broadened, in posterior view. Female: cerci plate-like (sub-genus 
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FDD8FC9AFEC2FC85" box="[557,709,848,874]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Galactomyia</emphasis>
- resembling 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FC9EFC9AF81AFC85" authorityName="Townsend" authorityYear="1915" box="[875,1053,848,874]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Ectophasiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FC9EFC9AF81AFC85" box="[875,1053,848,874]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ectophasiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="53AF4FDD9E69FFE6FBD8FC9AF876FC85" box="[1069,1137,848,874]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionTargetBox="[345,1238,1442,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[345,1243,1434,1909]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 3. Female terminalia. A. Ectophasiopsis gradata (Wiedemann, 1830) comb. nov. B. E. ypiranga sp. nov. Abbreviations: C = Cerci; s7 = Sternite 7; s8 = Sternite 8. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3829850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3829850/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A–B), or cerci widely separated basally with converging apical portions elongate and slender, forceps-like (subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FF1FFC52FD76FC5D" authorityName="Berthold" authorityYear="1827" box="[234,369,920,946]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Trichopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FF1FFC52FD76FC5D" box="[234,369,920,946]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trichopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
– see image of 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FDCFFC52FFA1FC5C" authority="in Sabrosky 1950" authorityName="in Sabrosky" authorityYear="1950" box="[570,934,920,947]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Polistomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FDCFFC52FEC1FC5D" box="[570,710,920,946]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Polistomyia</emphasis>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="AF052EA99E69FFE6FD07FC52FFA1FC5C" author="Sabrosky" box="[754,934,920,947]" firstAuthor="Sabrosky" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="361 - 371" refId="ref12747" refString="Sabrosky C. W. 1950. Notes on Trichopodini (Diptera, Larvaevoridae); with description of a new parasite of cotton stainers in Puerto Rico. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences 40: 361 - 371." type="journal article" year="1950">Sabrosky 1950</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) ………… 
<taxonomicName id="0C9428DB9E69FFE6FBDBFC52F970FC5D" authority="Berthold, 1827" authorityName="Berthold" authorityYear="1827" box="[1070,1399,920,947]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Trichopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F9E08F4A9E69FFE6FBDBFC52F8BEFC5C" bold="true" box="[1070,1209,920,947]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trichopoda</emphasis>
Berthold, 1827
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
